\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset

As mentioned in a previous section, the length of the key is determined
 by the number of bits that were transmitted by Alice in the same basis
 as the one Bob used to measure them, leading to its correct interpretation
 (meaning that if Alice transmitted a '1' Bob also measured a '1').
 According to our model, the probability Alice and Bob chose the same basis
 for a certain bit is 
\begin_inset Formula $50\%$
\end_inset

.
 In both the experiment and simulation it appears that the length of the
 key is close to the expectancy according to the model (which is half of
 the sequence length).
 Moreover, in the experiment and simulation all the bits that were measured
 and transmitted in the same basis by Bob and Alice respectively were correctly
 interpreted.
 This is exactly as the model predicts and as we require for the protocol
 to work (in its most ideal case, in reality communication errors can and
 will occur, but the protocol can still allow its users to deduct the existence
 of a spy).
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
I'm not 100% sure about this phrasing.
 The protocol obviously prefers that there are no errors due to communication
 problems but even if there are some and like 6% of the bits have errors
 even though they were measured in the same basis we can still deduce the
 existence of an eavesdropper.
 What do you think? I think the phrasing is fine
\end_layout

